{
  "card_id": "weekly_profile",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Weekly Profile",
  "aliases": [
    "Classic Expansion Week",
    "Consolidation Reversal Weekly Profile",
    "Weekly Candle Profile",
    "weekly candle profile",
    "周度价格框架",
    "周线框架"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A framework for anticipating which day forms the weekly high or low and trading continuations toward higher-timeframe objectives. It uses accumulation-manipulation-distribution phases, failure swings for standard deviation projections, and daily candle closures with hourly change in state of delivery for confirmation.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify Monday as accumulation phase; avoid trading.",
    "Identify midweek reversal (often Wednesday) as Change in State of Delivery (CISD).",
    "Identify Thursday as manipulation phase, price breaks midweek reversal point.",
    "Identify Friday as distribution phase, price continues Thursday direction and may reach standard deviation targets.",
    "Use failure swings (not simple highs/lows) to project standard deviation lines (±2, ±2.5, ±4, ±4.5).",
    "Identify order blocks, propulsion blocks, and fair value gaps as support/resistance within the weekly framework.",
    "Establish weekly directional bias by identifying the weekly draw on liquidity (prior range highs/lows, failure swings).",
    "Observe daily chart for a candle 2 closure (sweep prior day's high/low and close back inside) on Monday or Tuesday, forming the weekly high (bearish) or low (bullish).",
    "Confirm reversal with an hourly CISD within that day: price closes through the series of opposing candles that formed the extreme.",
    "Days preceding the reversal should close opposite the weekly bias to create the wick.",
    "If the reversal candle is not clean, wait for a candle 3 closure the following day as additional confirmation.",
    "After confirmation, anticipate 2-3 expansion days toward higher timeframe objectives; trade continuation until average daily range or a key level is reached.",
    "In classic expansion, the first three days expand in the bias direction, leaving a daily fair value gap.",
    "In midweek reversal, look for a retracement day (often Thursday) that reverses back into the weekly range with SMT divergence at a key level; then trade continuation.",
    "In consolidation reversal, if Mon-Wed ranges are small without directional expansion, wait for Thursday to manipulate the range (e.g., take out Monday's high and close back inside) with candle 2 closure and hourly CISD, then trade Friday continuation.",
    "After reversal confirmation, use the previous day's equilibrium to frame continuation: the next day's low (bullish) or high (bearish) should hold in the upper/lower half.",
    "Align weekly profile with daily profile and phases of price (expansion/retracement/consolidation/reversal); do not apply as a rigid template.",
    "Friday may cap the weekly range with a retracement (TGIF) once the higher timeframe objective is met."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The Weekly Profile sets higher-timeframe directional bias by identifying which day forms the weekly extreme, then trading continuation on subsequent days toward HTF objectives. After confirmation via daily candle 2 closure and hourly CISD, expansion days offer entries targeting prior highs/lows, failure swings, or average daily range. It provides a framework for daily and intraday alignment, especially when fractal model setups are unclear. Friday often caps the weekly range with a retracement.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Trading on Monday or before high-impact news, ignoring accumulation phase uncertainty.",
    "Using simple weekly high/low for standard deviation projections instead of failure swings, leading to inaccurate targets.",
    "Failing to identify midweek reversal (CISD), missing the manipulation-distribution key turn.",
    "Ignoring propulsion block mean threshold (candle body midpoint), causing premature stop loss.",
    "Not filtering with economic calendar, getting induced during news volatility.",
    "Expecting every weekly profile to be picture-perfect and mechanically applying a template instead of using phases of price and logic.",
    "Acting on a candle 2 closure or reversal day without first confirming an hourly CISD within the reversal day's range.",
    "Acting on a weak or absent candle 2 closure without waiting for lower-timeframe confirmation or a candle 3 closure.",
    "Trying to predict in advance which day forms the weekly high/low rather than letting it form and reacting.",
    "Calling a weekly extreme too early (e.g., on Wednesday) when that day is itself an expansion candle, before another day confirms.",
    "Treating a Tuesday doji that takes out both sides of the range as providing directional information.",
    "Treating every failure swing as a relevant draw on liquidity before price demonstrates expansion away from it.",
    "Trading away from failure swings without first seeing a reversal signature confirming intent.",
    "Continuing to anticipate expansion after the HTF key level has already been hit, missing the Friday retracement cap."
  ],
